  "Idea": "This research proposes a novel, self-evolving framework called \u2018BiasRefiner\u2019 that leverages implicit human feedback and adversarial learning to dynamically improve a RoBERTa-based political stance classifier\u2019s ability to detect and explain structurally embedded biases in AI-generated summaries. While existing methods treat stance classification as static or rely on fixed annotation schemas, BiasRefiner treats bias detection as a continuous learning problem informed by real-time user interactions. When users reject, ignore, or manually revise a generated summary, these actions are interpreted as implicit negative feedback. A dedicated adversarial module—the Feedback Synthesizer—learns to convert this sparse behavioral signal into plausible, natural language critiques (e.g., 'This summary downplays environmental risks while emphasizing job losses, which may reflect a conservative lean'). These synthesized critiques are then used to fine-tune both the stance classifier (to better recognize nuanced framing patterns) and the summarization model (to generate more balanced outputs). Crucially, the Feedback Synthesizer is trained via adversarial imitation: it generates critique candidates, while a discriminator distinguishes them from actual human-written critiques collected in controlled studies. Over time, the system learns to produce increasingly realistic and actionable feedback, closing the loop between detection, explanation, and mitigation. To evaluate effectiveness, we deploy the system in a simulated news aggregation environment where users interact with AI summaries of politically charged topics. We measure longitudinal improvements in classifier precision, reduction in cross-partisan disagreement, and increased user trust. By transforming passive stance detection into an adaptive, behavior-driven process, this work pioneers a new paradigm for ethically robust summarization systems that evolve alongside their audiences.",
